Andre Morales, a 36-year-old from Brooklyn, arrived before 3:00 a.m. Tuesday and planned to ask Hillary Rodham Clinton how it felt to work for President Obama after he had defeated her in the 2008 Democratic primary.

Donna Gabrielle, a 65-year-old retiree, said she wanted to get here at 2:00 p.m. on Monday to be first in line, but she couldn’t make it until 4:00 a.m. on Tuesday. Jacqueline Corsentin, 21, a college student, is writing her senior thesis on why Mrs. Clinton would make a good president. She arrived at the flagship Barnes & Noble in Union Square from New Jersey at 6:00 a.m.

